            "heading": "The Vision Framework — Mountains and Valleys (56:1-4)",
            "body": "[C] Enoch is transported to a mountainous region where he sees 'a deep valley with burning fire' and kings and mighty ones being cast into it. [B] The valley of judgment echoes [A] the Valley of Hinnom (Gehenna), which becomes the standard metaphor for eschatological punishment in Second Temple literature (cf. [A] Isaiah 66:24, [A] Mark 9:43-48). [C] The 'kings and the mighty' represent earthly rulers who have oppressed God's people — a recurring theme throughout the Parables (chs. 46, 48, 53, 62-63). <br><br>[C] The geographical setting may allude to actual locations in the Transjordan or northern regions where Parthian invasions would be expected to occur. [C] R.H. Charles suggests this could reference the valley east of Jerusalem, but the cosmic scope of the vision transcends specific geography. [B] The point is theological: those who wielded unjust power on earth will be brought low, their authority stripped away in the presence of the Son of Man and the Lord of Spirits.<br><br>[A] This pattern follows the OT prophetic tradition where earthly tyrants face both temporal and eternal judgment ([A] Isaiah 14:3-23 against the king of Babylon, [A] Ezekiel 28:1-19 against the prince of Tyre). [C] The Enochic innovation is the explicit connection to the heavenly court and the Son of Man figure who executes the sentence."
