            "body": "[C] The critical verse: 'In those days the angels shall return and hurl themselves to the east upon the Parthians and Medes: they shall stir up the kings, so that a spirit of unrest shall come upon them' (56:5). The verb 'stir up' (Hebrew הֵעִיר <em>he'ir</em>, Greek ἐγείρω <em>egeirō</em>) is the same used in [A] Jeremiah 51:11 ('YHWH has stirred up the spirit of the kings of the Medes'). [B] This establishes direct continuity between the OT prophetic oracle and the Enochic apocalyptic vision.<br><br>[C] The 'angels' here are most likely the loyal members of the divine council, acting as God's agents to execute judgment. [B] This contrasts with the fallen Watchers of 1 Enoch 6-16, who acted in rebellion. [C] George Nickelsburg notes that the Enochic corpus distinguishes between categories of angels: Watchers (fallen), archangels (loyal executors), and the general angelic host (messengers and warriors). [C] The angels in 56:5 belong to the latter category — they are instruments of divine providence in history.<br><br>[C] The Parthian Empire is specifically named, grounding this vision in the geopolitical realities of the late Second Temple period. The Parthians defeated Rome at Carrhae (53 BC) and again during Mark Antony's campaign (36 BC). [C] By the time of the Parables' composition (likely 1st century BC or early 1st century AD), Parthia represented the greatest military threat to Roman hegemony. [C] For Jewish apocalyptic writers, this made Parthia a natural candidate for the role of God's 'rod of anger' against the oppressive empire (cf. [A] Isaiah 10:5 where Assyria is called 'the rod of my anger').<br><br>[C] The phrase 'spirit of unrest' (πνεῦμα ἀκαταστασίας) suggests both psychological agitation and spiritual influence. [B] The kings are not merely making strategic decisions — they are being supernaturally compelled toward conflict. This removes human agency as the ultimate cause and places responsibility with the divine council's decree."
