            "body": "[C] The text describes a specific sequence: (1) angels act, (2) kings are roused from thrones, (3) they 'spring up as lions from their lairs' and 'go forth like hungry wolves.' [C] The animal imagery — lions and wolves — is drawn from [A] OT prophetic literature where predatory animals symbolize ruthless military powers ([A] Jeremiah 5:6, [A] Ezekiel 22:27, [A] Zephaniah 3:3). [B] The imagery conveys both ferocity and divine orchestration: these are not random raids but calculated invasions directed by heavenly decree.<br><br>[C] The phrase 'rouse them from their thrones' is significant. [C] In ancient Near Eastern royal ideology, the throne symbolizes stable, divinely sanctioned rule. To be 'roused' from the throne implies forced mobilization — the kings are compelled to leave their seats of power and enter the field of battle. [B] This suggests that the invasion is not opportunistic but driven by forces beyond normal political calculation. [C] The Parthian kings, historically, did conduct western campaigns against Roman client states in Syria and Judea, but these were typically defensive or retaliatory. [C] The Enochic vision presents a future escalation: a full-scale invasion of 'the land of the elect.'<br><br>[C] Verse 6 continues: 'And they shall go up and tread under foot the land of His elect ones.' [C] The 'land of the elect' is most naturally understood as Judea/Israel, though [B] the theological category 'elect ones' (ἐκλεκτοί) includes all faithful followers of the covenant, not merely ethnic Israel. [C] Throughout the Parables, the 'elect' and 'righteous' are those who remain faithful under persecution (cf. 1 Enoch 1:1, 48:1, 62:8). [B] The invasion, then, is a test and a catalyst for the final judgment — the oppressed will be vindicated, and the oppressors (both earthly and angelic) will be condemned."
        },
