            "body": "[C] Verse 7 shifts to agricultural metaphors: 'The land of His elect ones shall be before them a threshing floor and a highway.' [A] The threshing floor is a standard OT image for judgment ([A] Isaiah 21:10, [A] Jeremiah 51:33, [A] Micah 4:12-13). [A] In Isaiah 21:10, Babylon is called 'my threshed and winnowed one' — the nation that threshed others will itself be threshed. [B] Here, the irony is that the land of the elect becomes the <em>site</em> of threshing, but [B] the ultimate result is the judgment of the invaders, not the destruction of the elect.<br><br>[C] The 'highway' (ὁδός) imagery may allude to [A] Isaiah 40:3 ('Prepare the way of the LORD') or [A] Isaiah 62:10 ('Build up the highway... for the people'). [B] In Isaiah, the highway is for the return of the exiles and the coming of God's salvation. [C] In 1 Enoch 56, the highway is the invasion route — but [B] this invasion paradoxically prepares the way for divine intervention. [C] The kings think they are conquering; in reality, they are walking into the trap of divine judgment.<br><br>[C] The wine press imagery appears in verse 7 (some manuscripts): the land will be 'trodden down' as grapes in a wine press. [A] This echoes Isaiah 63:1-6, where God treads the wine press of the nations in judgment, and [A] Revelation 14:19-20, where the angel 'threw [the grapes] into the great wine press of the wrath of God.' [B] The wine press produces blood, symbolizing the violence of judgment. [C] Joel 3:13 combines the images: 'Put in the sickle, for the harvest is ripe. Go in, tread, for the wine press is full. The vats overflow, for their evil is great.' [B] The harvest and vintage are ripe — the time for judgment has come."
