            "body": "[C] The chapter concludes with hope: 'But the city of my righteous shall be a hindrance to their horses, and they shall begin to fight among themselves... until they wade in their own blood' (56:8, Charles translation). [C] The 'city of the righteous' likely refers to Jerusalem, though [B] in Enochic theology it may also symbolize the eschatological community of the faithful, wherever they are gathered. [B] The point is that the righteous are protected — the invasion does not succeed in destroying them.<br><br>[C] The phrase 'they shall begin to fight among themselves' is crucial. [B] This is not a victory won by human military might but by divine confusion of the enemy. [A] The pattern appears throughout the OT: [A] Judges 7:22 (Gideon's battle: 'YHWH set every man's sword against his comrade'), [A] 1 Samuel 14:20 (Saul's battle: 'every Philistine's sword was against his fellow'), [A] 2 Chronicles 20:23 (Jehoshaphat's battle: the invaders 'destroyed one another'). [B] When God fights for his people, the enemy self-destructs.<br><br>[C] The image of wading in their own blood is hyperbolic but follows [A] Ezekiel 38:21 ('Every man's sword will be against his brother') and [A] Zechariah 14:13 ('A great panic from YHWH shall fall on them, so that each will seize the hand of another, and the hand of the one will be raised against the hand of the other'). [B] The invaders are destroyed not by the elect but by the judgment of God, which turns their own violence back upon themselves.<br><br>[C] The final image is the 'hand of the righteous' rising against the kings (56:8). [B] This does not contradict the self-destruction motif — rather, [B] it indicates that after the enemy is thrown into confusion, the righteous participate in the final mopping-up operation. [C] This parallels the War Scroll's vision where the Sons of Light fight alongside the angelic armies after Michael strikes the decisive blow. [B] Human participation in divine judgment is a sign