            "heading": "Theological Synthesis — History as Divine Council Drama",
            "body": "[B] 1 Enoch 56 presents a sophisticated theology of history: earthly events are the visible manifestation of heavenly decrees. [A] This aligns with Daniel's vision of angelic princes governing nations (Dan 10:13, 20-21) and [A] Paul's statement that 'we do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against... the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly places' (Eph 6:12). [B] The Parthian invasion is both a real geopolitical event and a spiritual operation directed by the divine council.<br><br>[C] The chapter serves multiple rhetorical purposes in the Parables: (1) It reassures the persecuted elect that their oppressors will face judgment. (2) It demonstrates that God controls history, using even pagan empires as instruments of his will. (3) It sets the stage for the final theophany and the Son of Man's judgment in chapters 62-63. [C] The Parthian invasion is the penultimate act — the final act is the appearance of the Elect One on the throne of glory.<br><br>[B] The hermeneutical key is recognizing that apocalyptic literature operates on multiple temporal planes simultaneously. [C] The 'Parthians and Medes' are historical entities, but they also function as types — archetypes of the nations in rebellion against God. [B] This allows the text to speak both to its original audience (facing Roman oppression with Parthia as a potential liberator) and to future readers (facing different empires but the same spiritual dynamics). [A] Revelation uses the same technique with 'Babylon' (clearly Rome in the 1st century AD, but also any oppressive world system in any era).<br><br>[C] Michael Heiser argues that the 'Deuteronomy 32 worldview' — where God disinherited the nations at Babel and assigned them to angelic overseers — is the key to understanding apocalyptic geopolitics. [B] When nations invade Israel, it is not merely a political conflict but a rebellion of the angelic princes against YHWH's authority. [B] The judgment of the nations is simultaneously the judgment of their angelic rulers ([A] Isaiah 24:21, [A] Psalm 82:6-7). [C] 1 Enoch 56 makes this explicit: angels initiate the invasion, and both angels and kings face the consequences."
